column4: For A level Physics you need to be confident using large numbers in calculations, which will usually mean using standard form (power of 10 notation). You need to be able to substitute values into equations and to solve equations to find values. You will need the basic trigonometry from your maths GCSE course and we will also use ideas of proportionality. If you decide to study Physics or Engineering at university, you will need more advanced material from A level Mathematics.

column4:
Galileo Galilei, one of the founding fathers of modern Physics, wrote: "Mathematics is the language in which God has written the universe." 

Physics is a very quantitative science; it deals with measurements and numerical predictions. Most physical laws are expressed as equations. Applying physics very often involves using or solving equations. And, because Physics deals with distances and spaces, ideas from geometry, especially trigonometry, are often needed to do Physics
